"Rasheed M.A., Unsworth R.K.F.","Long-term climate-associated dynamics of a tropical seagrass meadow: Implications for the future",2011,"Marine Ecology Progress Series","422",,,"93","103",,,10.3354/meps08925,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-79551717216&partnerID=40&md5=1a82df744bcfb86be52bb7f1890ffe1d","Marine Ecology Group, Northern Fisheries Centre, Fisheries Queensland, Department of Employment, Economic Development and Innovation, PO Box 5396, Cairns, QLD 4870, Australia; Biological Sciences Research Unit, Glyntaf Campus, University of Glamorgan, Pontypridd CF37 1DL, United Kingdom","Rasheed, M.A., Marine Ecology Group, Northern Fisheries Centre, Fisheries Queensland, Department of Employment, Economic Development and Innovation, PO Box 5396, Cairns, QLD 4870, Australia; Unsworth, R.K.F., Biological Sciences Research Unit, Glyntaf Campus, University of Glamorgan, Pontypridd CF37 1DL, United Kingdom","The long-term changes of tropical intertidal seagrass, mainly Halodule uninervis and Halophila ovalis meadows and their relationship to climate are poorly documented. Developing a greater understanding of the effects of climate on seagrass meadows is critical for estimating the effects of future climate change scenarios. Here we document the temporal dynamics of coastal intertidal seagrass in tropical northeast Australia over 16 yr of detailed monitoring. This study is the first to directly relate such change to long-term climate variability in the Indo-Pacific region and southern hemisphere. Regression modelling was used to relate seagrass biomass and meadow area measurements to climate data. The aboveground biomass and area of the meadow were correlated with the interacting factors of air temperature, precipitation, daytime tidal exposure and freshwater runoff from nearby rivers. Elevated temperature and reduced flow from rivers were significantly correlated (R2 = 0.6, p &lt; 0.001) with periods of lower seagrass biomass. Results of this study have important implications for the long-term viability of seagrasses with regard to climate change scenarios. Modelling of our findings indicates that future higher temperatures could be detrimental to Indo-Pacific intertidal, coastal and estuarine seagrass meadows. © Inter-Research 2011.","Australia; Climate change; Global warming; Halodule uninervis; Halophila ovalis; Indo-Pacific; Queensland; Rainfall; Temperature","air temperature; biomass; climate change; ecoregion; future prospect; high temperature; intertidal environment; long-term change; meadow; rainfall; seagrass; Southern Hemisphere; temperature effect; Australia; Queensland; Halodule uninervis; Halophila ovalis",,,,,,"Agawin, N.S.R., Duarte, C.M., Fortes, M.D., Uri, J.S., Vermaat, J.E., Temporal changes in the abundance, leaf growth and photosynthesis of three co-occurring Philippine seagrasses (2001) Journal of Experimental Marine Biology and Ecology, 260 (2), pp. 217-239. , DOI 10.1016/S0022-0981(01)00253-2, PII S0022098101002532; Amand, M., Pelletier, D., Ferraris, J., Kulbicki, M., A step toward the definition of ecological indicators of the impact of fishing on the fish assemblage of the Abore reef reserve (New Caledonia) (2004) Aquatic Living Resources, 17 (2), pp. 139-149. , DOI 10.1051/alr:2004022; Aragones, L.V., Lawler, I.R., Foley, W.J., Marsh, H., Dugong grazing and turtle cropping: Grazing optimization in tropical seagrass systems? (2006) Oecologia, 149 (4), pp. 635-647. , DOI 10.1007/s00442-006-0477-1; Bjork, M., Uku, J., Weil, A., Beer, S., Photosynthetic tolerances to desiccation of tropical intertidal seagrasses (1999) Marine Ecology Progress Series, 191, pp. 121-126; Bjorndal, K.A., Nutritional ecology of sea turtles (1985) Copeia, 1985, pp. 736-751; (2010) Australian Federal Bureau of Meteorology Weather Records., , www.bomgov.au, BOM (Bureau of Meteorology) Available at; Bros, W.E., Cowell, B.C., A technique for optimising sample size (replication) (1987) J Exp Mar Biol Ecol, 114, pp.